                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\frac{1}{3}x^3 + \frac{1}{4}x^2 - 2x - 1</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T_3(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>k_0 + k_1 x + k_2 x^2 + k_3 x^3</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>x^2 + \frac{1}{2}x - 2</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T_3'(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>k_1 + 2 k_2 x + 3 k_3 x^2</m></cell>
                </row>                
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>2x + \frac{1}{2}</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T_3''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>2 k_2 + 6k_3 x</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T_3'''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>6k_3</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T_3(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>k_0</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T_3'(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>k_1</m></cell>
                </row>                
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\frac{1}{2}</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T_3''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>2k_2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T_3''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>6k_3</m></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
            </table>

        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            We see that <m>T_3(0) = f(0)</m> implies <m>k_0 = -1</m>; <m>T_3'(0) = f'(0)</m> implies <m>k_1 = -1</m>; <m>T_3''(0) = f''(0)</m> tells us <m>2k_2 = \frac{1}{2}</m>, so <m>k_2 = \frac{1}{4}</m>; and <m>T_3'''(0) = f'''(0)</m> shows that <m>6k_3 = 2</m>, so <m>k_3 = \frac{1}{3}</m>.  Thus <m>T_3(x) = \frac{1}{3}x^3 + \frac{1}{4}x^2 - 2x - 1</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
              We notice that <m>T_3(x) = f(x)</m> so <m>T_3(x)</m> perfectly approximates <m>f(x)</m> for every value of <m>x</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            We expect that <m>T_4(x) = T_3(x) = f(x)</m> because there's no better polynomial approximation to <m>f(x)</m> than <m>T_3(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If we find the degree <m>6</m> approximation to any function <m>f(x)</m> that is itself a degree <m>6</m> polynomial, we expect that the degree <m>6</m> approximation will be the original polynomial function itself.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      
    </solution>
